# JaCoCo Implementation Guide

## Overview
JaCoCo (Java Code Coverage) is a free code coverage library for Java, which analyzes test coverage of your code. This guide provides a simple configuration for implementing JaCoCo in any Maven-based Java project.

## Current Project Configuration Analysis

### Current Setup
The catalogo-items-service project uses JaCoCo Maven Plugin version **0.8.11** with the following configuration:

- **Java Version**: 17
- **Spring Boot Version**: 2.5.7
- **Build Tool**: Maven

### Key Features in Current Configuration
1. **Agent Initialization**: Prepares JaCoCo agent for code coverage collection
2. **Report Generation**: Creates HTML and XML reports after tests
3. **Quality Gates**: Enforces minimum 70% instruction coverage
4. **Exclusions**: Excludes configuration, DTOs, mappers, and controllers from coverage

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Add JaCoCo Plugin to pom.xml

```xml
<plugin>
    <groupId>org.jacoco</groupId>
    <artifactId>jacoco-maven-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>0.8.11</version>
    <executions>
        <!-- Initialize JaCoCo agent -->
        <execution>
            <id>jacoco-initialize</id>
            <goals>
                <goal>prepare-agent</goal>
            </goals>
        </execution>
        
        <!-- Generate coverage report -->
        <execution>
            <id>jacoco-site</id>
            <phase>test</phase>
            <goals>
                <goal>report</goal>
            </goals>
        </execution>
        
        <!-- Enforce coverage rules -->
        <execution>
            <id>default-check</id>
            <goals>
                <goal>check</goal>
            </goals>
            <configuration>
                <rules>
                    <rule>
                        <limits>
                            <limit>
                                <counter>INSTRUCTION</counter>
                                <minimum>70.0%</minimum>
                            </limit>
                        </limits>
                    </rule>
                </rules>
                <excludes>
                    <!-- Add your exclusions here -->
                    <exclude>com/yourpackage/config/**</exclude>
                    <exclude>com/yourpackage/dto/**</exclude>
                    <exclude>com/yourpackage/mapper/**</exclude>
                    <exclude>com/yourpackage/controller/**</exclude>
                </excludes>
            </configuration>
        </execution>
    </executions>
</plugin>
```

### Step 2: Basic Configuration Options

#### Plugin Version
```xml
<version>0.8.11</version> <!-- Latest stable version -->
```

#### Coverage Rules
You can configure multiple coverage metrics:

```xml
<rules>
    <rule>
        <limits>
            <!-- Instruction coverage (recommended) -->
            <limit>
                <counter>INSTRUCTION</counter>
                <minimum>70.0%</minimum>
            </limit>
            
            <!-- Branch coverage -->
            <limit>
                <counter>BRANCH</counter>
                <minimum>60.0%</minimum>
            </limit>
            
            <!-- Class coverage -->
            <limit>
                <counter>CLASS</counter>
                <minimum>80.0%</minimum>
            </limit>
            
            <!-- Method coverage -->
            <limit>
                <counter>METHOD</counter>
                <minimum>75.0%</minimum>
            </limit>
            
            <!-- Line coverage -->
            <limit>
                <counter>LINE</counter>
                <minimum>70.0%</minimum>
            </limit>
        </limits>
    </rule>
</rules>
```

#### Exclusions
Exclude packages/classes from coverage analysis:

```xml
<excludes>
    <!-- Configuration classes -->
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/config/**</exclude>
    
    <!-- DTOs and models -->
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/dto/**</exclude>
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/model/**</exclude>
    
    <!-- Mappers -->
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/mapper/**</exclude>
    
    <!-- Controllers (optional) -->
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/controller/**</exclude>
    
    <!-- Main application class -->
    <exclude>com/yourpackage/YourApplication.class</exclude>
    
    <!-- Generated classes -->
    <exclude>**/generated/**</exclude>
    
    <!-- Test classes -->
    <exclude>**/*Test.class</exclude>
    <exclude>**/*Tests.class</exclude>
</excludes>
```

### Step 3: Running JaCoCo

#### Basic Commands
```bash
# Run tests with coverage
mvn clean test

# Generate coverage report
mvn jacoco:report

# Check coverage rules
mvn jacoco:check

# All in one (test + report + check)
mvn clean test jacoco:report jacoco:check
```

#### Integration with Test Phase
The configuration above automatically runs JaCoCo during the `test` phase, so simply running:
```bash
mvn clean test
```
Will generate coverage reports.

### Step 4: Viewing Reports

After running tests, JaCoCo generates reports in `target/site/jacoco/`:

- **HTML Report**: `target/site/jacoco/index.html`
- **XML Report**: `target/site/jacoco/jacoco.xml` (for CI/CD integration)
- **CSV Report**: `target/site/jacoco/jacoco.csv`

Open the HTML report in your browser:
```bash
open target/site/jacoco/index.html
# or
xdg-open target/site/jacoco/index.html
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Coverage Targets
- **Instruction Coverage**: 70-80% (realistic for most projects)
- **Branch Coverage**: 60-70% (more challenging but valuable)
- **Avoid 100% obsession**: Focus on critical business logic

### 2. Exclusions Strategy
- **Always exclude**: Configuration, DTOs, models, mappers
- **Consider excluding**: Controllers (if only testing service layer)
- **Never exclude**: Business logic, service classes, utilities

### 3. Integration Strategy
- **Run with every build**: Ensure consistent coverage tracking
- **Fail builds on threshold drops**: Prevent coverage regression
- **Use in code reviews**: Reference coverage reports in PR discussions

### 4. Report Analysis
- **Focus on red areas**: Uncovered code in critical paths
- **Investigate yellow areas**: Partially covered complex conditions
- **Monitor trends**: Track coverage changes over time

## Troubleshooting

### Common Issues

#### 1. No Coverage Data
```bash
# Ensure agent is properly initialized
mvn clean jacoco:prepare-agent test
```

#### 2. Empty Reports
Check that tests are actually running and executing code:
```bash
mvn clean test -Dmaven.test.failure.ignore=true
```

#### 3. Build Failures
Adjust coverage thresholds or exclusions:
```xml
<minimum>50.0%</minimum> <!-- Lower threshold -->
```

### Debug Mode
Enable debug logging:
```bash
mvn clean test -X
```

## Complete Minimal Example

```xml
<build>
    <plugins>
        <plugin>
            <groupId>org.jacoco</groupId>
            <artifactId>jacoco-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>0.8.11</version>
            <executions>
                <execution>
                    <id>prepare-agent</id>
                    <goals>
                        <goal>prepare-agent</goal>
                    </goals>
                </execution>
                <execution>
                    <id>report</id>
                    <phase>test</phase>
                    <goals>
                        <goal>report</goal>
                    </goals>
                </execution>
                <execution>
                    <id>check</id>
                    <goals>
                        <goal>check</goal>
                    </goals>
                    <configuration>
                        <rules>
                            <rule>
                                <element>BUNDLE</element>
                                <limits>
                                    <limit>
                                        <counter>INSTRUCTION</counter>
                                        <value>COVEREDRATIO</value>
                                        <minimum>0.70</minimum>
                                    </limit>
                                </limits>
                            </rule>
                        </rules>
                    </configuration>
                </execution>
            </executions>
        </plugin>
    </plugins>
</build>
```
